 here where the blower is, as you can see right there. Um, and I'm probably gonna change out this cord. It's a super heavy duty cord, and I have this thing set on super low, so I'm only probably drawing about two amps off of that. I'm gonna put a lower heavy lower uh duty cord on there and use that cord for something else. Anyway, here we go. So this is the final product. This is my fan attached to a couple four-inch uh little holes that go to a little box so I can control the pressure because the fan is oversized for the job. You're only looking for a little puff of air, and these go to these pipes which connect to some irrigation pipes. And then this is my pile. Now, this is about a week old now. It's about 10 days old. And so this pile is uh, I wanna say about two and a half feet tall. It started out four feet tall and uh it has shrank quite a bit because of the action going on. And the real trick here is this is a little compost thermometer. See the very long probe on it. And you stick this in here. There we go. And this should climb to about 140. Uh right now we are in the thermophilic stage of the pile, which means it is over 130 degrees, but we like to keep it under 158 because that's where it starts to do damage. So 140 is real proper. We're enjoying that temperature. That's a good breakdown without getting too hot because with the pitched pile, you can never get it too hot because you're aerating it constantly, and when you do that by pitching it, you're actually distributing the heat. And with the static pile, which we will not turn, you want to make sure it doesn't get too hot because that can get uh a runaway temperature effect, and then it can be hard to cool these things. Um every 30 minutes for about 30 seconds, uh, we will this fan will turn on and it will push air into this pile, and that is how the microbes get their oxygen. This is an aerated static pile. We're very excited about it. It's the next stage of composting, and we no longer have to pitc